Test suite (`cargo test`) porting `test/snippet.test.ts`, validating `steno`'s snippet-rendering and Plover-key-building pipeline against the real `dict.steno` corpus loaded from the repo root (`../../dict.steno` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`). It exercises `parse_source`, `expand_dict`, `parse_template`, `render_snippet`, and `build_snippets`, so it breaks if any of those change output shape, or if `dict.steno` itself changes in ways that remove/rename the strokes this file hardcodes.

The doc comment explains a deliberate deviation from the TS original: the upstream tests targeted stroke `STKWR-LT` for the single-landing `${0}` and escaping cases, but that stroke's corpus meaning was repurposed (now a `let` binding). Rather than following the corpus, `template_literal()` reconstructs the intended `` `${%0}` `` template entry by hand via `parse_template` + a manually-built `Entry`/`TypedEntry`, bypassing the corpus for those two tests (`single_landing_is_exit`, `escapes_literals_not_tabstops`). If `dict.steno` changes further, only the corpus-driven tests are affected — this synthetic entry is stable.

Key helpers: `corpus()` reads the file (returns `io::Result`); `typed()` parses+expands the whole corpus into `Vec<TypedEntry>` (returns `None` on any failure — test failures from this show up as `unwrap()` panics, not assertion messages); `by_stroke(entries, stroke)` looks up by exact full stroke string; `tabstop_count(body)` counts `${0}`..`${9}` occurrences only (not `${10}`+).

Notable invariants asserted, not just tested incidentally: non-terminal "family root" strokes (entries that are a `/`-prefix of another entry's stroke, e.g. `STKWR-PBGS`) must never be `terminal` and must never get a sentinel-wrapped Plover token — only plain `{^}text{^}` — because the nvim plugin must not intercept them (they get superseded by a longer chord and Plover self-corrects via backspacing). `no_terminal_is_a_prefix_of_another_stroke` is a corpus-wide regression guard for this exact class of bug. `tokens_resolve_to_bodies` parses the sentinel-wrapped token format directly (`{^}` + `SENTINEL_OPEN` + key + `SENTINEL_CLOSE` + `{^}`) to cross-check every terminal's Plover value resolves to an entry in `build.snippets`, and asserts the corpus yields >1000 snippet bodies — a coarse regression tripwire on corpus size. Depends on `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` string constants matching whatever the nvim plugin/runtime parses elsewhere — if those sentinel strings change, this file's string-stripping logic must change too.